# 3. “つまらない”

Veteran Director: And now, without further ado, I hereby declare the directors' course open.
Sakaki: I'm not one for formalities, so I'll be keeping things casual from here on out.
Sakaki: And I think it's high time we introduced our other teacher.
Tom: <“Hello. Can you all hear me?”>
Sakaki: “Yes, we can hear you. We can also see your bedhead, Tom.”
Tom: <“Excellent. That means we're all set to begin.”>
Rui: (It's not surprising that two world-class directors such as them would be on speaking terms...)
Rui: (But they seem like old friends.)
Sakaki: Ah, I almost forgot. We'll be constantly switching back and forth between English and Japanese during this workshop.
Sakaki: I'll be sure to translate any especially technical terms or phrases, but this is also training for when you go overseas for work in the future. So, try to keep up.
Sakaki: Please feel free to use the translation functions on your smartphones and computers. Tom will be doing just that.
Tom: <“Hello, everyone. I won't be able to be there in person due to work scheduling, but I've been looking forward to this workshop for a very long time.”>
Tom: <“I may be a teacher for this workshop, but I'm sure you all have much to teach me too.”>
Tom: <“So, let's make the most of our time together.”>
Veteran Director: We'll start by going over the workshop's goals.
Veteran Director: The objective of the directors' course is to have you all produce shows from scratch.
Veteran Director: We'll have you approach this assignment as though you're developing a show to be performed on stage at ArcLand.
Rui: In other words, this show will need to meet the park's world-class standards...
Rui: Not only will it have to appeal to a wide range of age groups, it will need a high degree of artistic mastery.
Veteran Director: We wish to see original ideas from all of you, so please refrain from deriving or adapting anything from existing works. Keeping it on the level of homage is fine.
Veteran Director: And as far as casts go, you'll need to ask the actors in the other workshop course.
Rui: (I see. In my case, I'll likely be asking Tsukasa and the others for their help.)
Sakaki: Try to keep your show's runtime around an hour.
Sakaki: You'll have a month to work on them. Then, we'll watch them and give you our assessments.
Sakaki: ArcLand has told us not to pull any punches, so please try to understand.
Young Director Ａ: It's even scarier when he says that with a smile...
Young Director Ｂ: But we'll learn more by them picking us apart, so let's try to do our best.
Tom: <“That's about it for the briefing. We're looking forward to seeing your shows.”>
Sakaki: Now then, we were going to call it there for the day...
Sakaki: But since we're all here, why don't we have ourselves a little test before you start working on your shows in earnest?
Young Director Ａ: A little test...?
Tom: <“There's no need for alarm, everyone. Think of it as a piece of homework which will help you get to know your workshop peers better.”>
Tom: <“The next time we meet, we'd like for you all to introduce yourselves through some short shows.”>
Rui: Introduce ourselves...?
Sakaki: You are directors, after all. Doesn't it make sense to let your direction do the talking?
Sakaki: The theme will be “rain”. We're looking for shows around three minutes in runtime, to be performed in the arcade by the main entrance to ArcLand.
Sakaki: Of course, your shows will actually be performed here in this meeting room, so please keep that in mind.
Sakaki: It'll be a one-man show. We'd like to get an unbiased sense of your directing styles, so we've chosen an actor in advance to remove that particular variable.
Sakaki: I'm sure you're all familiar with Asahi Genbu.
Rui: ...!
Rui: (I see. Asahi can handle any role, so they'll immediately be able to see each director's capabilities.)
Rui: (It's the best way for them to size us up.)
Sakaki: Please have scripts and directing plans ready by next time.
Sakaki: Bring something good, okay?
Rui: Alright, this is the arcade where our shows will theoretically be staged.
Rui: Since it's so close to the entrance, guests of all ages should be present...
Rui: I'll want a show which fits in with the magical world of ArcLand, and also heightens anticipation and excitement for the wonderful time the guests are about to enjoy.
Rui: (Still... I feel like I'm dreaming. Tom Gray himself will see this show...)
Rui: (A show to introduce myself... It's no simple task, but I need to do my best.)
Rui: To achieve that ArcLand feel, I'll want to include some elements of magic and fantasy.
Rui: Also, since this is my self-introduction, I'll need to tie in something which refers to me personally.
Rui: I know. I can revive some of the ideas I used for those surprise shows I did all those years ago...
Asahi: “Argh! Why?! It always rains on the days when I have something important planned!”
Asahi: “The princess and I can't have our wedding in this weather!”
Asahi: “Oh, you're completely soaked.”
Asahi: “Would you like to rest at my house? I have some hot soup.”
Rui: (This is fascinating...)
Rui: (With all of us working with the same theme, each director's style is clearly visible. I'm learning so much.)
Rui: (And more importantly...)
Sakaki: That line at the end needs to carry a bit more implication.
Sakaki: As it is now, things just end as a normal, day-to-day conversation. Try to be more conscious of impactful phrasing.
Young Director Ａ: I understand.
Tom: <“I appreciated the boldness of your story structure. Devices like that will help keep your audience's attention.”>
Veteran Director: I agree. Be careful not to rely overmuch on props, but...
Rui: ...
Rui: (Their feedback, born from their wealth of experience, covers every conceivable angle. Each and every remark from them is a pearl of directing wisdom.)
Rui: (That alone makes my decision to participate in this workshop worth it.)
Veteran Director: Next, we have Kamishiro. You're our last one.
Rui: Thank you. Are you ready, Asahi?
Asahi: I'm ready.
Asahi: “Hey, have you seen them before?”
Asahi: “What am I talking about? The special flowers that bloom only during rainy days!”
Asahi: “I came to look for them after hearing reports of sightings around here.”
Veteran Director: The story of a botanist who wanders into the park in search of flowers that only bloom during rainy days.
Veteran Director: And through that search, he and the audience share special experiences you can only have when it rains, yes?
Rui: That's correct.
Tom: <“What a wholesome story. It should appeal to children and grown adults alike.”>
Tom: <“Also, forgive me if I'm mistaken... But have you ever happened to watch 'The Voices of Honeybees'?”>
Rui: “I have.”
Rui: “The shot of all the umbrellas seeming to bloom like flowers in the rain was very memorable.”
Tom: <“Yes, I knew it!”>
Tom: <“I'm impressed. That show's so old that footage of it doesn't really exist anymore.”>
Rui: (I had intended to avoid directly paying homage to his work...)
Rui: (But it seems it came through all the same.)
Sakaki: ...
Veteran Director: I have no further comments. Would you like to say anything, Mr. Sakaki?
Sakaki: Well...
Sakaki: I thought it was put together well. Your eye and technique go far beyond that of any ordinary high schooler.
Young Director C: He did really well...
Young Director Ｂ: Yeah, this is the first time Mr. Sakaki's showered someone with so much praise.
Rui: (No, this is...)
Sakaki: But that's about it.
Sakaki: I enjoy family-oriented stories quite a lot. They seem simple, but many of them have deep depths too.
Sakaki: But that doesn't apply to yours.
Sakaki: You've shown us something quite insipid... Kamishiro.
